"Krachler M., Zheng J., Fisher D., Shotyk W.","Global atmospheric As and Bi contamination preserved in 3000 year old arctic ice",2009,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","23","3", GB3011,"","",,,10.1029/2009GB003471,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77950884029&partnerID=40&md5=5294b466c529162457991cf134ed6597","Institute of Earth Sciences, University of Heidelberg, Im Neuenheimer Feld 236, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany; Geological Survey of Canada, 562 Booth Street, Ottawa, ON K1A0E4, Canada","Krachler, M., Institute of Earth Sciences, University of Heidelberg, Im Neuenheimer Feld 236, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany; Zheng, J., Institute of Earth Sciences, University of Heidelberg, Im Neuenheimer Feld 236, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany, Geological Survey of Canada, 562 Booth Street, Ottawa, ON K1A0E4, Canada; Fisher, D., Geological Survey of Canada, 562 Booth Street, Ottawa, ON K1A0E4, Canada; Shotyk, W., Institute of Earth Sciences, University of Heidelberg, Im Neuenheimer Feld 236, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany","Despite its growing environmental significance, there are no detailed historical records of atmospheric As deposition for the Northern Hemisphere. Having overcome the severe analytical challenges in measuring As in polar ice, and using an Arctic ice core representing ∼16 ka of snow accumulation, we present a complete record of atmospheric As deposition for this period which reveals significant contamination beginning 3000 years ago. While Pb enrichments unequivocally increased threefold above natural background levels during Greek/Phoenician, Roman, and Medieval periods, As is elevated by a factor of 5. Previous studies showed that these periods are not only enriched in Pb but also Sb: here we show significant contamination not only by As but also Bi, Cu, and Zn. The Pb isotope data reveal declines in the ratio 206Pb/ 207Pb which reflects the introduction Pb-bearing aerosols from smelting of lead ores, but the metallurgy of copper ores must also have played a role. Taken together, these findings demonstrate a deeper, broader environmental significance of sulphide ore processing in antiquity, defining the origins of global atmospheric contamination for a suite of related elements and providing a new perspective on the start of the Anthropocene. In addition, the data indicate that by far the greatest As concentrations in the ice core are recorded during the Younger Dryas cold climate event centered around 12 ka B.P., demonstrating the strong link between global climate change and the atmospheric cycling of trace elements. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Analytical challenge; Anthropocene; Arctic ice; Atmospheric contamination; Cold climate; Copper ore; Environmental significance; Global climate changes; Historical records; Ice core; Natural backgrounds; Northern Hemispheres; Pb isotopes; Polar ice; Snow accumulation; Strong link; Sulphide ores; Younger Dryas; Aerosols; Contamination; Copper smelting; Ice; Isotopes; Lead smelting; Ores; Trace elements; Zinc; Climate change; antimony; arctic environment; arsenic; atmospheric deposition; atmospheric pollution; bismuth; climate change; global perspective; historical record; ice core; mineral exploration; paleoclimate; Roman era; Younger Dryas; Arctic",,,,,,"Bear, F.E., (1964) Chemistry of the Soil, , 2nd ed., 515 Reinhold, New York; Boutron, C.F., Candelone, J.-P., Hong, S., Past and recent changes in the large-scale tropospheric levels of lead and other heavy metals as documented in Antarctic and Greenland snow and ice (1994) Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 58, pp. 3217-3225. , doi: 10.1016/00167037(94)90049-3; Emsley, J., (2001) Natures Building Bloch: An A-Z Guide to the Elemente, , Oxford Univ. Press, New York; Fyfe, W.S., The environmental crisis: Quantifying geosphere interactions (1981) Science, 213, pp. 105-110. , doi:10.1126/science.213.4503.105; Gabrielli, P., Barbante, C., Boutron, C., Cozzi, G., Gaspari, V., Planchon, F., Ferrari, C., Cesco